[Blue-green algae, or cyanobacteria, can be deadly to a number of animals and have been responsible for the deaths of livestock in other parts of the world (see ProMED postings below). Cyanobacteria can be found in water, soil, on rocks, and even in symbiotic relationships with some lichens. They can be found as single cells, colonies, filaments, sheets, and sometimes balls with a hollow center.

Cyanobacteria have several types of classification, but some produce cyanotoxins. Some of the toxins are known as anatoxin-a, anatoxin-as, aplysia toxin, cylindrospermopsin, domoic acid, microcystin LR, nodularin R (from _Nodularia_), and saxitoxin. These toxins are neurotoxic, hepatotoxic, cytotoxic, and endotoxic. These toxins have been detrimental to a wide variety of animals, but can also be dangerous to humans.

Although this is Australia, the information on the Canadian website regarding human health is pertinent. Additional information about cyanobacteria, especially as they relate to human health, can be found at the Health Canada website at http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/ewh-semt/pubs/water-eau/cyanobacter-eng.php.

Images of cyanobacteria can be seen at
http://www-cyanosite.bio.purdue.edu/images/images.html. - Mod.TG

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3810134,186.]
